  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real barrier I've seen firsthand in my work. As a transgender electrician who's spent years fixing wires and circuits in Chicago's industrial zones, I've noticed how stereotypes about who belongs in technical fields can make people feel invisible. When someone tells me, 'You're not supposed to be good at this,' it's not just a comment—it's a psychological weight. Stereotype threat happens when people internalize negative expectations about their group, like girls in math or minorities in engineering, and it makes them perform worse under pressure. I've seen it in my own community, where some young people avoid STEM because they think they're 'not the type' for it. That's why addressing it matters: it's not about fixing people, but about changing the environment so everyone feels safe to try. In my shop, I've started sharing stories about how I overcame stereotypes—like how I learned to read electrical diagrams as a kid without anyone telling me I was 'too slow.' We need to normalize conversations about these issues in schools and workplaces, not just in academic papers. It's about creating spaces where everyone's worth isn't tied to a stereotype. And that's something we can do together, starting with listening more and speaking up when we see someone being held back by a label.",
